column1: two years ago i decided to stop killing myself with alcohol and see what i was really capable of when i walked into @passagesmalibu determined to transform
in the past 24 months i have:

alcohol is one of the most powerful and addictive drugs on the planet and no one removes it from their diet despite the transformation potential. instead in the middle of an epidemic of substance abuse sobriety is social suicide but i was heading in a very very dangerous downward spiral so i decided social suicide was preferable. kate spade was too ashamed to admit this and get help because of the stigma.

sobriety is the most challenging and frustrating and rewarding experience of my life but i can't speak openly about it without judgement. even after all of my transformation and success i struggle with feeling lonely and isolated at times
column2: i am unable to find a romantic relationship and am heading into my tenth year of being single.

column1: i have downplayed the severity of the drinking because i was ashamed but i was consistently drinking destructively for many many years. i am incredibly grateful that i never hurt anyone else but everyday i wake up without a hangover is literally a miracle.

pain doesn't go away and life isn't perfect for me but everyday in the past two years has been better than any day i was drinking. i am hopeful that one day sobriety will be as mainstream and accepted as gay marriage is.
we used to keep so many things hidden and we have changed in so many amazing ways to accept people but we don't accept sobriety
i was told many times over the past two years to ""get to a meeting "" and "" no one likes people like you"" we need to end the stigma attached to alcoholics

column1: 44206;instagram;2019-02-07 07:53:23;FALSE;"quote of the day is a poem because i needed to find this and you needed to read it. iâ€™ve been working so hard and doing so well for myself. and i slept through my alarm â€” because i was having night terrors all of (my) night due to my ptsd. i woke up paralyzed and like something was strangling me. but i got up out of bed. i went to work. iâ€™m proud of myself even if i have to be gentle with myself today. traumas and ptsd will always be with us. we have to learn the coping skills in order to push through the day. we have to treat ourselves kindly on our bad days. bad mental days will happen even if youâ€™re working on yourself and youâ€™re doing great. sometimes your trauma will sneak up and attack you again. but we are survivors. we are safe now. and we are making sure we live. we are not alone because we have each other. .

column1: garnier micellar water is one of the most popular products among beauty bloggers.
it comes in a plastic bottle with a flip-top.
how to use: pour it on a cotton pad and gently clean your face with it. it can be used to remove eye

my experience: i bought the one in the picture ^ and have used it several times to remove my makeup. it takes at least five cotton rounds to remove a full face of makeup with this micellar water. it isn't harsh
column2: doesn't cause irritation or acne but stings my eyes a little. i wash my face with a face wash after removing my makeup with it.

column1: using the micellar water on its own isn't enough in my opinion. to make sure your face is totally clean
column2: wash/cleanse your face after taking the makeup off with micellar water.

column1: the bottle says ""no rinse"" but it leaves a film on your face if you don't wash. so i won't recommend not rinsing.
you can use it 20 to 40 times depending on how much and how often you wear makeup. the bottle claims 'up to 60 uses' which is an overstatement but considering the price 20 - 40 times is great.
final verdict: it is a great product for its price. if you are on a budget and can't afford buying expensive makeup removing products
column2: garnier micellar water is a good option.

column1: i'm... reeling... from the ending of this book. i'm not sure if i like it. like never let me go
column3: painful social commentary. in this case
column4: throwing unrequited male desire into the light.

column1: rejecting unwanted male advances can be dangerous. rejection is often met with anger
column2: sometimes this anger turns to violence
column3: sometimes to other destructive but not necessarily physical means. those doing the rejecting are branded a slut
column5: told that they were leading the rejected on. anything to avoid the fact the the male in question was undesired.

column3: i was out with @whatsallyreadnext and some of her friends. we were at a bar and a group of city men invited us to sit at their table and drink with them. we ended up at another bar with them
column5: i didn't want to miss my last train. so i said my goodbyes. one from the group followed me out
column7: i owed him more for the drinks that me and my friends had consumed. i told him firmly that i wasn't interested in anything more. i offered to pay
column10: the bar had a bouncer and i was only a short walk from the tube station. but i was shook. i called my stepdad on the train home and asked him to pick me up. it was 4am. he didn't ask why
column11: he must have heard it in my voice. as soon as he arrived
column12: i burst into tears. i cried all the way home. i cried when he gave me a hot chocolate. i cried while telling him what had happened. i cried feeling stupid for being so scared. but i was scared.

column1: it wasn't just that i felt threatened or unsafe. i felt dirty
all of those feelings have been dragged back up again
column2: every time a man has sought to ""take me down a peg"" because i rejected him. there was no indication that the ending would be quite so... triggering. and now i'm feeling a little drained from it.

column1: 44221;instagram;2019-02-07 06:11:59;FALSE;"this poem resembles some of what us survivors have to overcome. being sexually abused takes a part of you. for most people

column3: at some point we have thought that we are not worthy or even questioned ourselves
column4: â€œwho would even want to be with a person like me?â€ we have thought that we are not in control because we have all experienced some sort of act of being powerless. before i shared my story
column5: for many years i felt as if i was the only one that had gone through this experience. now that i have opened up to others
column6: many have opened up to me. some were strangers and some were those that i have known very well. if you are a survivor

column1: last week i posted an fb status about how i love my iyengar teacher's old-school style. one of my yoga teacher friends @razieli commented that she was curious about why i liked this approach as she had found it off-putting and changed her mind about going for an iyengar training (see screenshots above).
it is an excellent question and today i had the time to collect my thoughts in reply:

column3: it is lunar new year and i haven't been keeping up much with posting. .

column1: i am with you. i don't wish to attend an iyengar training. it's not something i was ever interested in doing. .
i'm fortunate to have had 2 iyengar teachers
column2: one of whom studied directly with bks iyengar in the 1960s. her gentle
column3: sensitive approach couldn't be more different from the strict
column5: authoritarian mode that the iyengar name is typically associated with. she was the reason i left academia to teach yoga. .

column2: i was lucky to meet an iyengar teacher in singapore whom i practise with now. he does not teach an ""advanced"" level class. he does mostly ""basic"" asana with a few inversions (sirsasana) that are always optional. on a side note
column3: that's not a pose i include in my practice (unless at a ropewall) and so i don't teach it either. .

column1: my passion for the iyengar method comes from watching the way that my 2 iyengar teachers combine an acute sensitivity to the individual student's condition. yes
column2: there are several ""classical"" poses i either don't teach or teach differently. that is my current path that i am making for myself: what to keep
column3: what to leave behind. the baseline is what is healthy & sustainable; and secondly what kind of a practice does the individual student need?

column1: i get that this may be problematic... to call what i teach an ""iyengar class"" although i'm no traditionalist. i have been considering renaming my class. if  you have any suggestions
column2: i'd be glad to hear them ğŸ˜‡ğŸ™ğŸ¼

#kamalaharris #imwithher #kamala2020 ""i will always speak with decency and moral clarity and treat all people with dignity and respect."" senator kamala harris

a daughter of a tamil indian immigrant mother and jamaican immigrant father - both social justice activists and doctors who went on to pursue the american dream and provide the best life they could for their daughters.

she wants that dream available to every american again because today we find ourselves in a place where it is out of reach for far too many and retirement with dignity has been replaced with our seniors working in fast food as as walmart clerks just to make ends meet.

let's #keepgoing and build on the successes of 2018 and mobilize our voters on the issues that matter most - quality of life - equity of opportunity and rights and justice - and fighting climate change because environmentalism and a robust economy are not mutually exclusive. â€ªhelp fuel this grassroots campaign!

column1: 44468;instagram;2019-02-07 01:51:51;FALSE;"ğŸ–¤my first #workinprogress is my second book. it wasn't meant to be my second book. my original second book is 100+ pages sitting on the back burner. this came first. i started this for a guy i was seeing who felt he was worthless
column2: and i wanted him to have a copy of every great moment we had together and how i felt about him. however
column3: things took a turn for the dark side. after being sexually assaulted
column4: i was confused and he abandoned me
column6: and i was still paying for his therapy while he was out dating other people. but i had these poems typed up for him already
column7: and my cousin told me to still publish them (along with all of the ones about the pain)
column8: and she gave me the title as well. thank you
column9: @circustree - it has been a healing process that is almost finished. if you swipe
column10: you'll get mostly the recent examples and i think two when i was still enamored with him.ğŸ–¤

column1: 44485;instagram;2019-02-07 00:50:50;FALSE;"what do i share in the in between? the space we occupy that is neither inspiring or exciting? when the words i want to utter sound like a broken record? what then?

life is different now but life is always different for us. we feel restless. wounds are healing and prospective adventures seem just out of reach. when will the next job come? the move? what state? what small wonders will the next campground hold? adoption? that was a big topic but where is that sense of excitement now? just out of reach as we stare blankly at indistinguishable growth.

column3: desperation and heartache deeply shape the person we are to become. although difficult to endure it is only in these moments of chaos that our character becomes strengthened and refined.
happiness and abundance allow our soul rest. we linger in the reprieve from the harsh world weâ€™ve undoubtedly endured. we may not grow in depth but we mature in the growth that got us here.

column1: but what about this? this season of in between. these seemingly insignificant moments that merge and blend together to create a static life. we are grateful yet indifferent. we are human

column1: 44522;instagram;2019-02-07 00:16:45;FALSE;"ok so this truck tried to follow me today.

i was on the phone with my granny when this pimple on society's ass pulls up in front of me blocking my path asking if i speak english. then he said he was looking to buy a house or something. i told him i don't live in the area
column2: i'm just here visiting my dad. he asks if that's where i'm going and asks to drive me there. i having been hit on by guys in cars before realized this was bad and said no and started to walk around his truck. he asks my name and i told him ""i don't tell personal info to strangers"". i had my grandma on speaker this whole time
column3: unknown to him. i wanted somebody to hear that. then as i walked away i told grandma i'd call her back and called my dad telling him i wanted him to come get me because i had to pee. meanwhile this guy is following me. i didn't know since my glasses are busted and without them i can't see that far. the scariest thing is that usually these creeps leave when they see me pull out my phone. i notice him following me still and waving at me and i start to dial the cops. before i can dial them he starts to pull over next to me. fortunately at the last minute before he gets out of his truck my dad pulled up. so he took off. i get in my dad's car and tell him that that guy was following and harassing me. dad was furious and started chasing the guy down in his car trying to get a photo of his liscence plate. the guy pulled over and went in a mexican restaurant and we went home.

column8: but hindsight is no good to anyone. just learn from it and try and apply it in the future.

column1: 44678;instagram;2019-02-06 22:23:04;FALSE;today has been a bit of an emosh one. the end of my first lot of group counselling sessions. i'm so so happy to have met some of the strongest most amazing ladies who have shown me so much support the last few months. more than some of my friends i've knowm for years have!! it's so nice for people to turn around and say 'your not alone' and 'me too'. i cannot thank every single lady in that group enough for just being so open and honest and most importantly ... non judgemental...cos for those 2 hours on a weds morning i've felt so safe
column2: supported and not felt like a crazy lady who is labelled as pnd. since that first session to now i and these ladies have made so much improvement...i still have a very long road ahead of me in this journey. so this is not an end. it's not goodbye... it's only just the beginning! i should also mention the lady who runs this group. i owe my life to her
column3: and i will forever be grateful to her for finding me at my absolute lowest and getting me to where i am. she is the most amazing lady who will forever be a hero in my eyes and words will never be enough to show my appreciation

column1: 44786;instagram;2019-02-06 20:47:44;FALSE;"i would be interested to know what catches your eye first? her skin? hair? age? we are fully aware slavery's human trafficking element however one should dive deeper into the #fancygirls area of #slavery. the aspect of sexual slavery was prevalent in most of the south and served as an economic booster to many of the southern cities that were often too populous for field slavery to have an effect. many of these women were african but the twist is what happens when the biracial child is born and grows up.

there were men that would buy slaves for the specific reason of sex or making the slave one of his wives. but the offspring from these interracial marriages posed both an opportunity and a problem for #antebellum south. because of the complexion of the child could be anywhere from fair to dark
column2: their life rested with the color of their skin from birth. a fair-skinned child may have the life of a standard white person in the south but because human trafficking was such a profit
column3: they may be sold into prostitution as early as 7. their skin tone was a rarity and therefore expensive. this would lead to darker-skinned white women being kidnapped and sold into prostitution slavery as well. .
